:"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Robert Crossebi of Oulcottis was born in Scotland as the son of Richard Crossebi of Oulcottis. He had at least 2 sons and 1 daughter with Mrs Robert Crossebi. He died in 1498."},"et":{"–1498":"–1498","–Female":"Surnud","1433–1498":"1433–1498","1435–Male":"1435–Surnud","1437–1484":"1437–1484","–Male":"Surnud","1437":"1437","1435":"1435","1433":"1433","1498":"1498","BEF 1498":"enne 1498","1484":"1484","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland","Torthorwald, Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Torthorwald, Dumfriesshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"–1498":"–1498","–Female":"Kuollut","1433–1498":"1433–1498","1435–Male":"1435–Kuollut","1437–1484":"1437–1484","–Male":"Kuollut","1437":"1437","1435":"1435","1433":"1433","1498":"1498","BEF 1498":"ennen vuotta 1498","1484":"1484","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Scotland":"Scotland","Torthorwald, Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Torthorwald, Dumfriesshire, Scotland"},"fr":{"–1498":"–1498","–Female":"Décédée","14